	<article class="comment-item" itemscope="itemscope" itemtype="http://schema.org/UserComments">
		<p class="comment-author" itemprop="creator" itemscope="itemscope" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/45435628abb56dd1acc9ac2ef104a2b1?s=48&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/45435628abb56dd1acc9ac2ef104a2b1?s=96&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' itemprop="image" />			<cite class="fn">tom</cite>		</p>
		<p class="comment-meta"> 
			<time class="comment-published" datetime="2015-12-08T15:05:14+02:00" title="Tuesday, December 8, 2015, 3:05 pm" itemprop="commentTime"><a href="https://texblog.org/2012/08/29/changing-the-font-size-in-latex/#comment-37728">8. December 2015 at 15:05</a></time>
					</p>
		<div class="comment-content">
			<p>Dear Kanchana,</p>
<p>Thanks for the files. A pointer to the class file or the <a href="https://uk.sagepub.com/en-gb/eur/manuscript-submission-guidelines" rel="nofollow">journal guidelines</a> would have been good enough.</p>
<p>Anyway, the font size is hard coded in the class file (first few lines of code and line 233 onwards). Therefore, you can&#8217;t and shouldn&#8217;t change the font size if you are submitting to a SAGE journal. You can use macros such as <code>\large</code> to change parts of your text. See the article above for more details.</p>
<p>Should you want to use this class for your own purposes, you have to make changes to the class file.</p>
<p>HTH, Tom</p>
		</div><!-- .comment-content -->
